<DOC><DOCNO> AP890725-0175 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1921EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-25 0392</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0410</SECOND><HEAD>Army Says It Repulsed Rebel Attack, Killing 180</HEAD><BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Government forces repulsed an assaultby Moslem guerrillas west of Kabul and killed 180 of the attackers,the government said Tuesday.   In other battles, government troops killed 58 rebels and threePakistanis, the officials said.   The reports were sketchy and impossible to verify independently,and the government mentioned only three fatalities of its own. Theonly date given was fot of Kabul, which reportedlyoccurred Saturday.   In that battle, guerrilla forces commanded by GulbaddinHekmatyar attacked government soldiers at Maidan r the attack wesShahr,capital ofWardak province, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad NabiAmani.   He said the guerrillas were driven back with many wounded, andthey had to abandon their 180 dead.   He said a large quantity of arms and ammunition was captured ordestroyed in the attack.   Hekmatyar is a leading member of the interim government createdto take over Afghanistan if the U.S.-backed rebels topple theSoviet-supported Marxist government in Kabul.   In the eastern province of Nangarhar, government troops attackedand killed 38 rebels, including a Hekmatyar commander, inretaliation for a guerrilla attack outside Jalalabad that killedtwo soldiers, the government said. It said 48 guerrillas werewounded.vernment also said three Pakistani military personnel werekilled when their jeep was attacked near Surkh Diwar, southeast ofJalalabad.   The Afghan government has repeatedly accused Pakistan offighting alongside the guerrillas. The most powerful rebel groupsare based in Pakistan, but Pakistan says it is not fighting withthem.   In Herat province near Iran, the Afghan government said, armytroops ambushed guerrillas, killing six of them while capturingarms and ammunition.   In southern Kandahar, near the Pakistani border, a guerrillaattack killed one soldier, and the military retaliated by killing14 rebels, the government said.   In Kabul, three more rockets injured five people, includingthree children, a government statement said. A total of at least 45people have died in rocket attacks in the capital since Saturday.   The government blames the guerrillas for the attacks. The rebelshave in the past accused the government of attacking its owncapital to throw the blame on them.</TEXT></DOC>